born 1958), [[American Kenpo]]\n*[[Mitsusuke Harada]] (born 1928), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Randall G. Hassell|Randall Hassell]] (born ''c.'' 1940), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Demetrius Havanas]] (1950-1981), style unspecified\n*[[Dave Hazard]] (born 1952), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Dana Hee]] (born 1961), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Sek\u014d Higa]] (1898\u20131966), [[G\u014dj\u016b-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Higa Yuchoku|Yuchoku Higa]] (1910\u20131994), [[Sh\u014drin-ry\u016b]] and [[G\u014dj\u016b-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Higaonna Kanry\u014d|Kanry\u014d Higaonna]] (1853\u20131915), [[G\u014dj\u016b-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Higaonna Kanryu|Kanryu Higaonna]] (1849\u20131922), [[Okinawan martial arts]]\n*[[Morio Higaonna]] (born 1938), [[G\u014dj\u016b-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Kori Hisataka]] (1907\u20131988), [[Shorinjiryu Kenkokan Karate|Shorinjiryu Kenkokan]]\n*[[Masayuki Hisataka]] (born 1940), [[Shorinjiryu Kenkokan Karate|Shorinjiryu Kenkokan]]\n*[[Steven Ho (martial artist)|Steven Ho]] (born 1973), style unspecified\n*[[Sam Hoger]] (born 1980), style unspecified\n*[[Russ Hogue]] (born 1974), style unspecified\n*[[Loek Hollander]] (born ''c.'' 1940), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n*[[Mark Holst]] (born 1984), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Kyoji Horiguchi]] (born 1990), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Andy Hug]] (1964\u20132000), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]] and [[Seidokaikan|Seido]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== I ==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Kazuyoshi Ishii]] (born 1953), [[Seidokaikan|Seido]]\n*[[Ank\u014d Itosu]] (1832\u20131916), [[Okinawan martial arts|Shuri-te]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== K ==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Nobuaki Kakuda]] (born 1961), [[Seidokaikan|Seido]]\n*[[Hirokazu Kanazawa]] (1931\u20132019), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Taiji Kase]] (1929\u20132004), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Hajime Kazumi]] (born 1971), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n*[[\u00d6mer Kemalo\u011flu]] (born 1987), style unspecified\n*[[Dave Kershaw]] (born 1955), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Katsunori Kikuno]] (born 1981), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n*[[Richard Kim (karate)|Richard Kim]] (1917\u20132001), [[Sh\u014drinji-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Davit Kiria]] (born 1988), [[Ashihara kaikan|Ashihara]]\n*[[Taishin Kohiruimaki]] (born 1977), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n*[[Yuki Kondo]] (born 1975), [[Shorinji Kempo]]\n*[[Takayuki Kubota]] (born 1934), [[Okinawan martial arts|Te]] and [[Gosoku-ryu]]\n*[[Sh\u014dg\u014d Kuniba]] (1935\u20131992), [[Shit\u014d-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Yasuaki Kurata]] (born 1946), [[Shito-ryu]]\n*[[Ch\u014dtoku Kyan]] (1870\u20131945), [[Sh\u014drin-ry\u016b]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== L ==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Maximiliano Larrosa]] (born 1992)\n*[[Joe Lewis (martial artist)|Joe Lewis]] (born 1944), [[Sh\u014drin-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Chuck Liddell]] (born 1969), [[American Kenpo]]\n*[[Bobby Lowe (karateka)|Bobby Lowe]] (1929\u20132011), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n*[[Dolph Lundgren]] (born 1957), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]] and [[G\u014dj\u016b-ry\u016b]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== M ==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Kenwa Mabuni]] (1889\u20131952), [[Shit\u014d-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Lyoto Machida]] (born 1978), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Midhun Jith]] (born 1989), [[Shito ryu]]\n*[[John Makdessi]], [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Akira Masuda]] (born 1962), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n*[[Shokei Matsui]] (born 1963), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n*[[Matsumura S\u014dkon|S\u014dkon Matsumura]] (''c.'' 1800\u2013''c.'' 1890), [[Okinawan martial arts|Shuri-te]]\n*[[Chuck Merriman]] (born ''c.'' 1940), [[G\u014dj\u016b-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Kenji Midori]] (born 1962), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n*[[Takayuki Mikami]] (born 1933), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Miyuki Miura]] (born 1949), [[Shotokan]] and [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n*[[Frank Mir]] (born 1979), [[American Kenpo|Kenp\u014d]]\n*[[Ch\u014djun Miyagi]] (1888\u20131953), [[G\u014dj\u016b-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Katsuya Miyahira]] (born 1918), [[Sh\u014drin-ry\u016b Shid\u014dkan]]\n*[[Ei'ichi Miyazato]] (1922\u20131999), [[G\u014dj\u016b-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Minoru Mochizuki]] (1907\u20132003), [[Shotokan]] and [[Yoseikan]]\n*[[Vic Moore]] (born 1943), [[Shuri-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Motobu Ch\u014dki|Ch\u014dki Motobu]] (1871\u20131944), [[Okinawan martial arts|Shuri-te]]\n*[[Motobu Ch\u014dy\u016b|Ch\u014dy\u016b Motobu]] (1857\u20131938), [[Okinawan martial arts|Shuri-te]]\n*[[Matt Mullins]] (born 1980), [[Sh\u014drei-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Musashi (kickboxer)|Musashi]] (Akio Mori, born 1972), [[Seidokaikan|Seido]]\n*[[Glen Murphy]] (Born 1957) [[Kyokushin]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== N ==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Sh\u014dshin Nagamine]] (1907\u20131997), [[Sh\u014drin-ry\u016b]] and [[Matsubayashi-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Don Nagle]] (1938\u20131999), [[Isshin-ryu]] \n*[[Tatsuya Naka]] (born 1964), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Andrews Nakahara]] (born 1983), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n*[[Tadashi Nakamura (martial artist)|Tadashi Nakamura]] (born 1942), [[Seid\u014d juku]]\n*[[Masatoshi Nakayama]] (1913\u20131987), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Sh\u016bgor\u014d Nakazato]] (born 1921), [[Sh\u014drin-ry\u016b Sh\u014drinkan]]\n*[[Jadamba Narantungalag]] (born (1975), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n*[[Gunnar Nelson (fighter)|Gunnar Nelson]] (born 1988), [[G\u014dj\u016b-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Alain Ngalani]] (born 1975), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n*[[J\u014dk\u014d Ninomiya]] (born 1954), [[Enshin kaikan|Enshin]]\n*[[Hidetaka Nishiyama]] (1928\u20132008), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Masaaki Noiri]] (born 1993), Shin\n*[[Chuck Norris]]  (born 1940), [[Shotokan]], [[Shito-ryu]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== O ==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Hideo Ochi]] (born 1940), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Tsutomu Ohshima]] (born 1930), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Teruyuki Okazaki]] (born 1931), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Terry O'Neill (martial artist)|Terry O'Neill]] (born 1948), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Hironori \u014ctsuka]] (1892\u20131982), [[Wad\u014d-ry\u016b]]\n*[[\u014cyama Masutatsu|Masutatsu \u014cyama]] (1923\u20131994), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== P ==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Ed Parker]] (1931\u20131990), [[American Kenpo]]\n*[[Cecil T. Patterson|Cecil Patterson]] (1930\u20132002), [[Wad\u014d-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Seth Petruzelli]] (born 1979), [[Shit\u014d-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Nicholas Pettas]] (born 1973), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n*[[Malcolm Phipps]] (born 1942), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Henry Pl\u00e9e]] (born 1923)\n*[[Karin Prinsloo (karateka)|Karin Prinsloo]] (born 1972), JKA [[Shotokan]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== R ==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Sam Roberts (politician)|Samuel Roberts]] (born 1956), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Hatsuo Royama]] (born 1948), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n*[[Bas Rutten]] (born 1965), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== S ==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Tarec Saffiedine]] (born 1986), Shihaishinkai\n*[[Georges St-Pierre]] (born 1981), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n*[[Kanga Sakukawa]] (1733\u20131815), [[Okinawan martial arts|Te]]\n*[[Masaaki Satake]] (born 1965), [[Seidokaikan|Seido]]\n*[[Katsuaki Sat\u014d]] (born 1946), Satojuku\n*[[Semmy Schilt]] (born 1973), [[Ashihara kaikan|Ashihara]]\n*[[Andy Sherry]] (born 1943), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Shimabuku Tatsuo|Tatsuo Shimabuku]] (1908\u20131975), [[G\u014dj\u016b-ry\u016b]] and [[Isshin-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Zenry\u014d Shimabukuro]] (1908\u20131969), [[Sh\u014drin-ry\u016b Seibukan]]\n*[[Hiroshi Shirai]] (born 1937), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Assuerio Silva]] (born 1974), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Wesley Snipes]] (born 1962), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Tiffany van Soest]] (born 1989), [[Sh\u014drin-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Paul Starling]] (born 1948), [[G\u014dj\u016b-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Shojiro Sugiyama]] (born 1929), [[Shotokan]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== T ==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Kazumi Tabata]] (born 1943), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Seigo Tada]] (1922\u20131997), [[G\u014dj\u016b-ry\u016b]] and [[Seigokan]]\n*[[Masaji Taira]] (born 1952), [[G\u014dj\u016b-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Peichin Takahara]] (1683\u2013''c.'' 1765), [[Okinawan martial arts|Te]]\n*[[Rina Takeda]] (born 1991), Ryukyu Shorin-ryu\n*[[Ch\u014djir\u014d Tani]] (1921\u20131998), [[Sh\u016bk\u014dkai]]\n*[[Ewerton Teixeira]] (born 1982), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n*[[Geoff Thompson (writer)|Geoff Thompson]] (born 1960), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Seikichi Toguchi]] (1917\u20131998), [[G\u014dj\u016b-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Kenji Tokitsu]] (born 1947), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Kanken T\u014dyama]] (1888\u20131966), [[Sh\u016bd\u014dkan]]\n*[[Robert Trias]] (1923\u20131989), [[Shuri-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Masami Tsuruoka]] (born 1929), [[Chit\u014d-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Ashraf Tai]], (career 1974\u20131985) [[Shotokan]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== U ==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Kanbun Uechi]] (1877\u20131948), [[Uechi-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Sadamu Uriu]] (born 1929), [[Shotokan]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== V ==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Luca Valdesi]] (born 1976), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Dominique Valera]] (born 1947), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Jean-Claude Van Damme]] (born 1960), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Will Vanders]] (born 1963), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]] and [[Shotokan]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== W ==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Atsuko Wakai]] (born 1971), [[Seigokan]] and [[G\u014dj\u016b-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Bill Wallace (martial arts)|Bill Wallace]] (born 1945), [[Sh\u014drin-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Shunji Watanabe]] (born 1938), [[Sh\u014drinjiry\u016b Kenk\u014dkan Karate|Shorinjiryu Kenkokan]]\n*[[John van Weenen]] (born 1941), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Michael Jai White]] (born 1967), [[Kyokushin]], [[Shotokan]], and [[G\u014dj\u016b-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Arturo Worrell]] (born 1950), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Ronnie Watt]] (born 1947), [[Shotokan]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Y ==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[James Yabe]]  (born 1941), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[Kents\u016b Yabu]] (1866\u20131937), [[Sh\u014drin-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Meitoku Yagi]] (1912\u20132003), [[G\u014dj\u016b-ry\u016b]]\n*[[Yutaka Yaguchi]] (born 1932), [[Shotokan]]\n*[[G\u014dgen Yamaguchi]] (1909\u20131989), [[G\u014dj\u016b Kai]]\n*[[Masahiro Yamamoto (kickboxer)|Masahiro Yamamoto]] (born 1983), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n*[[Terutomo Yamazaki]] (born 1947), [[Kyokushin kaikan|Kyokushin]]\n*[[Tony Young (martial artist)|Tony Young]] (born 1962), [[G\u014dj\u016b-ry\u016b]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Karateka}}\n[[Category:Karateka| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of martial artists]]\n[[Category:Karate-related lists]]\n", "name_user": "103.82.13.159", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_karateka"}
{"title_page": "Quebec Bulldogs", "text_new": "{{short description|Ice hockey team from 1878 to 1920}}\n{{For|the former minor league baseball team known as the '''Quebec Athletics'''|Quebec Athletics (baseball)}}\n{{NHL Team\n|CAN_eng = 1\n|team_name = Quebec Bulldogs\n|bg_color = background:#FFFFFF; border-top:#3E5EFF 5px solid; border-bottom:#3E5EFF 5px solid;\n|text_color = #000000\n|logo_image = QuebecBulldogs.png\n|founded = 1878<ref name=\"battfields-1878\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ccbn-nbc.gc.ca/_en/site-rassembleur.php?section=2 |title=Welcome to the Plains of Abraham |publisher=Government of Canada |accessdate=2008-11-10}}</ref>\n|history = '''Quebec Hockey Club'''<br />1878\u20131888 (independent)<br />1889\u20131890 ([[Amateur Hockey Association of Canada|AHAC]])<br />1891 (dormant)<br />1892\u20131898 ([[Amateur Hockey Association of Canada|AHAC]])<br />1899\u20131905 ([[Canadian Amateur Hockey League|CAHL]])<br />1906\u20131909 ([[Eastern Canada Amateur Hockey Association|ECAHA]])<br />1910 ([[Canadian Hockey Association (1909\u20131910)|CHA]])<br />1910\u20131917 ([[National Hockey Association|NHA]])<br />1917\u20131919 (dormant)<br />'''Quebec Athletic Club'''<br />1919\u20131920 ([[National Hockey League|NHL]])<br />'''[[Hamilton Tigers (ice hockey)|Hamilton Tigers]]'''<br />1920\u20131925\n|arena = [[Quebec Skating Rink]] 1878\u20131913<br />[[Quebec Arena]] 1913\u20131920<ref name=\"times-arena\">{{cite news |work=New York Times |title=WINTER SPORTS IN QUEBEC.; First Snow Start a Season of Which Much Is Expected |page=XX5 |date=December 13, 1913}}</ref>\n|city = [[Quebec City|Quebec City, Quebec]]\n|team_colors = Blue, white<br>{{color box|#3E5EFF}} {{color box|#FFFFFF}}\n|stanley_cups= '''2''' ([[1911\u201312 NHA season|1912]], [[1912\u201313 NHA season|1913]])\n}}\n\nThe '''Quebec Bulldogs''' were a men's senior-level [[ice hockey]] team based in [[Quebec City]], Quebec, Canada. The team was officially known as the '''Quebec Hockey Club''',<ref>Farrell, pg. 77</ref> and later as the '''Quebec Athletic Club.''' One of the first organized ice hockey clubs, the club debuted in 1878 with the opening of the [[Quebec Skating Rink]]. The club continued as an amateur team through various leagues, eventually becoming professional in 1908. The club would play in the [[National Hockey Association]] (the forerunner to the NHL) and the [[National Hockey League]]. In 1920, the team moved to [[Hamilton, Ontario]] and became the [[Hamilton Tigers (ice hockey)|Hamilton Tigers]].\n\n==Franchise history==\n\n===Amateur roots, 1878\u20131909===\n[[File:Quebec Hockey Club 1891-92.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Quebec Hockey Club in 1891\u201392. Players are Bertram Patton, Herbert Bignell, Arthur Dickson Scott, Charles Smith, Arthur Edward Scott, Herbert Scott, Robert Davidson and [[David Watson (general)|David Watson]].]]The Quebec Hockey Club was founded in 1878, after the construction of the Quebec Skating Rink in 1877.<ref name=\"battfields-1878\"/> The club consisted of Anglo-Canadian players. Play was by exhibition only, against teams drawn from the club members or visiting teams from Montreal. In 1883, the club played in the [[Montreal Winter Carnival ice hockey tournaments|Montreal Winter Carnival]], and joined the [[Amateur Hockey Association of Canada]] (AHAC) in 1888 and were members until 1898. After the AHAC, Quebec played in the [[Canadian Amateur Hockey League]] from 1899 to 1905, and the [[Eastern Canada Amateur Hockey Association]] from 1906 to 1909. One player that went through the ranks of the Quebec Hockey Club was [[David Watson (general)|David Watson]] (1869\u20131922), a journalist and newspaper owner who fought as a Major-General in [[World War I]]. Watson played for the Quebec HC as a cover point (an offensive defenceman) in the AHAC through the course of the 1890s.\n\nThe club came close to winning the Stanley Cup on two occasions. In the [[1894 AHAC season|1894 season]] Quebec tied for the AHAC regular season lead with three other clubs. The AHAC drew up plans to hold the playoff solely in Montreal. Quebec declined to play in Montreal without one game in Quebec and the championship was eventually won by the [[Montreal Hockey Club]]. In 1904, Quebec won the CAHL outright. In a dispute, the club did not win the [[Stanley Cup]] or challenge for it. The [[Ottawa Hockey Club]] was the defending champions in [[1904 CAHL season|1903\u201304]], but withdrew from the league. Quebec went on to win the CAHL and expected to receive the Stanley Cup as league champions. The trustees of the Cup instead ruled that the Cup went to Ottawa.\n\nTwo significant players on the Quebec Hockey Club during the later part of the first decade of the 1900s were [[Charles Gavan Power|Chubby]] and [[Joe Power (ice hockey)|Joe Power]], who both later would be serve as politicians in Quebec. A third Power brother, [[James Power (ice hockey)|Rockett Power]], also represented the club.\n\n===National Hockey Association===\n\nIn late 1909, Quebec became a founding member of the [[Canadian Hockey Association (1909\u20131910)|Canadian Hockey Association]] (CHA) in 1909. The CHA, however, would only last one month before being absorbed into the much more powerful [[National Hockey Association]] (NHA). Rejected by the new league, the Bulldogs sat out the inaugural [[1910 NHA season|1910]] season. The following season, [[1910\u201311 NHA season|1910\u201311]], the Bulldogs took over the defunct [[Cobalt Silver Kings]] franchise, but had a rough initiation, finishing dead last with four wins and 12 losses in a 16-game season. On a positive note, and a sign of things to come, [[Jack Patrick McDonald|Jack McDonald]] scored 14 goals and [[Tommy Dunderdale]] scored 13.\n\nFor [[1911\u201312 NHA season|1911\u201312]], the Bulldogs went from worst to first, with [[Joe Malone (ice hockey)|Joe Malone]] having a spectacular season, to win the [[O'Brien Trophy (ice hockey)|O'Brien Cup]] as champions of the NHA and the [[Stanley Cup]]. The Dogs' record improved to 10 wins and eight losses while Malone scored 21 goals and Jack McDonald scored 18. In a Stanley Cup challenge, they crushed the [[Moncton Victorias]] in two games, 9\u20133 and 8\u20130, in the best-of-three [[playoff]].\n\n[[Image:Quebec Bulldogs, 1911 logo.png|right|thumb|150px|Logo used (1911\u20131913).]]\nIn their third season ([[1912\u201313 NHA season|1912\u201313]]), Quebec would again finish first overall with a record of 16-4 losses to retain the championship. Joe Malone won the scoring race with an unprecedented 43 goals. His teammate, [[Tommy Smith (ice hockey)|Tommy Smith]], was a close second with 39. In a Stanley Cup challenge after the season the team easily beat the [[Sydney Millionaires (MaPHL)|Sydney Millionaires]] in two games by a combined score of 20-5.\n\nThe [[Victoria Aristocrats]] of the [[Pacific Coast Hockey Association]] next challenged the Bulldogs. The powerhouse Bulldogs expected to bowl over the Aristocrats, but were shocked after splitting the first two games and then losing 6\u20131 in the decisive third game. However, the Stanley Cup Board of trustees did not recognise the challenge because it should have been played in Quebec. PCHA leader Lester Patrick refused. The Bulldogs were able to keep the Cup.\n\nIn December 1913, the Bulldogs moved to the new [[Quebec Arena]].<ref name=\"times-arena\"/> The following seasons would see the Bulldogs drop from the top of the league. They would finish third overall in each of the next three seasons and in the last NHA season ([[1916\u201317 NHL season|1916\u201317]]) went second overall. After their two Stanley Cup wins, though, they would never again challenge for the Cup.\n\n===National Hockey League and the move to Hamilton 1917\u20131925===\nThe Bulldogs, along with the [[Montreal Canadiens]], [[Montreal Wanderers]] and [[Ottawa Senators (original)|Ottawa Senators]], were frustrated with [[Toronto Blueshirts]] owner [[Eddie Livingstone]]'s acrimonious dealings.  However, they discovered that the league constitution did not allow them to simply vote Livingstone out.  Instead, the four clubs joined in founding the [[National Hockey League]] in 1917, and did not invite Livingstone to join them. Quebec's long-time manager [[Mike Quinn (ice hockey)|Mike Quinn]] had retired due to ill health.  The other directors of the Bulldogs were unable to get enough financing to make the move to the NHL\u2014no small consideration given that Quebec City was by far the smallest market in the league.  They opted to suspend operations for the league's [[1917\u201318 NHL season|inaugural season]].{{sfn|Wong|2005|p=76}} To balance out the schedule, the remaining three clubs granted a temporary franchise to the Toronto Arena Company; the direct ancestors of today's [[Toronto Maple Leafs]].\n\nIn 1918, the franchise was sold in principle to [[Percy Quinn]]. However, Quinn's actual intent was to use the Bulldogs to help resurrect the NHA.  However, the other owners called Quinn's bluff by demanding a firm commitment to ice a team in the NHL for the [[1918\u201319 NHL season|1918\u201319 season]].  When Quinn refused to do so, the NHL canceled the franchise.{{sfn|Wong|2005|p=78}} When no other Quebec-based group came forward, the Bulldogs sat out the 1918\u201319 season as well.\n\nIn May 1919, NHL president Calder and Mike Quinn made efforts to return Quebec to the league. Calder suggested that Quinn apply to the league for a new franchise. On December 2, 1919, the NHL approved the application of the Quebec Athletic Club for an NHL franchise.{{sfn|Wong|2005|p=78}} Newspapers at the time now referred to the team as the ''Quebec Athletics''<ref>{{cite book |title=The Official National Hockey League 75th anniversary commemorative book |publisher=McClelland & Stewart |location=Toronto |last=Diamond |first=Dan |year=1991 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/officialnational0000unse/page/26 26] |isbn=0-7710-6727-5 |url=https://archive.org/details/officialnational0000unse/page/26 }}</ref> rather than ''Bulldogs''.\n\nWhile the team had been suspended, their star player, [[Joe Malone (ice hockey)|Joe Malone]], played for the Canadiens. Malone rejoined the franchise, and won the scoring championship that year with 39 goals. Despite Malone's scoring and the presence of players like [[Harry Mummery]], Quebec had a dismal season, finishing last, with 4 wins and 20 losses.\n\nBefore the 1920\u201321 season, the NHL took back the franchise, and sold it to new owners who moved the team to Hamilton, where it became the Tigers. This helped to head off a potential competing league organized by Livingstone from setting up in Hamilton.<ref>{{cite book|title=Deceptions and Doublecross: How the NHL conquered hockey |last=Holzman | first=Morey | year=2001 | publisher=Dundurn Press}}</ref>\n\nThe Tigers played in the NHL from [[1920\u201321 NHL season|1920]] to [[1924\u201325 NHL season|1925]]. Due in large part to a team players' strike in the 1925 NHL playoffs, the franchise was revoked a second time that summer, this time for good.  The entire Tigers roster was then sold to [[Bill Dwyer (gangster)|Bill Dwyer]], owner of the expansion [[New York Americans]] franchise. However, the NHL does not reckon the Americans as a continuation of the Bulldogs/Tigers franchise.  The Americans would play in the NHL from [[1925\u201326 NHL season|1925]] to [[1941\u201342 NHL season|1942]].\n\nThe last active Bulldogs player in major-league hockey was [[Dave Ritchie (ice hockey)|Dave Ritchie]], who retired in 1926. The last active Bulldog player was [[Eddie Oatman]], who played pro hockey until 1939 and played against the CAHL Quebec Beavers in 1929.\n\nOver time, various hockey teams played in Quebec, including the minor-pro [[Quebec Castors]] and [[Quebec Aces]]. Big-league hockey would not return to Quebec City until the [[Quebec Nordiques]] were founded in 1972 as part of the new [[World Hockey Association]]. They joined the NHL in 1979. However, as with the Bulldogs, they found the going difficult playing in the league's smallest market.  They moved to [[Denver]] in 1995 as the [[Colorado Avalanche]]. A [[potential National Hockey League expansion]] bid for Quebec City has been tabled by the league's board of governors since 2015.\n\n==Season-by-season record==\n* 1888\u20131898 \u2013 [[Amateur Hockey Association of Canada]]\n* 1899\u20131905 \u2013 [[Canadian Amateur Hockey League]]\n* 1906\u20131909 \u2013 [[Eastern Canada Amateur Hockey Association]]\n* Jan. 1910 \u2013 [[Canadian Hockey Association (1909\u20131910)|Canadian Hockey Association]]\n* 1910\u20131917 \u2013 [[National Hockey Association]]\n* 1919\u20131920 \u2013 [[National Hockey League]]\n\n'''''Note:''' GP = Games played, W = Wins, L = Losses, T = Ties, Pts = Points, GF = Goals for, GA = Goals against''\n{| cellpadding=5\n|- bgcolor=\"#dddddd\"\n! Season || GP || W || L || T || Pts || GF || GA || Finish || Postseason\n|-\n| [[1888\u201389 AHAC season|1888\u201389]] || 1 || 0 || 1 || 0 || \u2013 || 2 || 3 ||colspan=\"2\" |lost one AHAC challenge 2\u20133 to Montreal HC.\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n| [[1890 AHAC season|1890]] || 1 || 0 || 1 || 0 || \u2013 || 1 || 5 ||colspan=\"2\" |lost one AHAC challenge 1\u20135 to Montreal HC.\n|-\n| [[1891 AHAC season|1891]] || 1 || 0 || 1 || 0 || \u2013 || 0 || 0 ||colspan=\"2\" |lost one AHAC challenge by default to Montreal HC.\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n| [[1892 AHAC season|1892]] || 2 || 0 || 2 || 0 || \u2013 || 3 || 6 ||colspan=\"2\" |lost two AHAC challenges to Ottawa HC.\n|-\n| [[1893 AHAC season|1893]] || 8|| 2|| 5||1|| 4|| 23|| 46||fourth, AHAC||''Did not qualify''\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n| [[1894 AHAC season|1894]] || 8|| 5|| 3||0||10|| 26|| 27||1st place tie, AHAC||''Did not participate''\n|-\n| [[1895 AHAC season|1895]] || 7|| 2|| 5||0|| 0|| 18|| 27||fifth, AHAC||''Did not qualify''\n|- bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n| [[1896 AHAC season|1896]] || 8|| 4|| 4||0|| 8|| 23|| 23||third